The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted on February [XXX], 2025 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. 
On February [XXX], 2025 at 8:12 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle operating in Culver City, California was in a collision involving a shopping cart.  
The Waymo AV was stopped at a red traffic light heading [XXX]. A pedestrian pushing a shopping cart approached the Waymo AV from behind and made contact with the left rear drivers side of the stationary Waymo AV.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode.  The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted on December 19, 2024 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. 
On December [XXX], 2024 at 10:28 AM PT, a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a Non-Motorist (scooterist) on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling west on [XXX] when it approached the intersection with [XXX]. A building was located at the intersection, just to the right of the Waymo AV. While the traffic light was green and as the Waymo AV approached the intersection with [XXX], a scooterist who was traveling south on the sidewalk of [XXX] and was previously occluded by the building became visible and entered the intersection against a red light. As the Waymo AV braked for the scooterist, the scooterist made contact with the passenger side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage and the scooterist reported a minor injury. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted on December 10, 2024 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. 
On December [XXX], 2024 at 5:14 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a scooter on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX] in a queue of traffic and slowed to a stop at the intersection with [XXX], which had a green light but did not have sufficient space for the Waymo AV to fully traverse and clear the intersection. A scooterist following behind the Waymo AV began to pass the Waymo AV on the left, and the front of the scooter made contact with the rear driver side of the stationary Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The scooterist immediately left the scene.  The Waymo AV was discovered to have sustained damage from the contact during a subsequent inspection of the vehicle on December 9, 2024.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was stopped for a red traffic light on northbound [XXX] while preparing to turn left onto westbound [XXX] in San Francisco. After the light turned green the Zoox vehicle began to move forward and then slowed gradually to yield to a pedestrian with right of way in the crosswalk on [XXX]. Just as the Zoox vehicle slowed to almost a stop (0.2 mph), a skateboarder quickly approached the rear of the Zoox vehicle extending their left arm forward and making contact with the right rear corner of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy and brought the vehicle to a stop. The skateboarder initially told the Zoox vehicle operator they were not injured but later mentioned they "smacked" their hand and it was "bruised." When asked, however, they declined medical attention. The Zoox vehicle did not sustain damage. The police were not called. The Zoox vehicle camera footage shows that the skateboarder was looking at their cell phone and did not appear to have been looking ahead at the roadway before the time of contact.The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

On June [XXX], 2023 at 3:39 PM PDT, an Apollo Autonomous Vehicle ("Apollo AV") operating in San Francisco, California, was in a collision involving a scooter on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Apollo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] passing the intersection with [XXX]. The intersection has stop signs clearly installed at all four ways, which require vehicles to make full stop before entering the intersection. The Apollo AV made a full stop, entered and passed approximately 75% of the intersection. A person on scooter coming southbound from [XXX],  approached the intersection. The person on scooter entered the intersection without stopping, then made contact with the passenger rear-side of Apollo AV. Our Apollo AV operator immediately disengaged the AV, pulled over to the closest safe place to park, got out of the car to check the person on scooter, who already left the scene on his scooter without exchanging any information. The Apollo AV had small minor paint scratch, which do not need repair. The police were not called.

On Tuesday May [XXX] at 16:40 local time, the May shuttle was driving Northbound from [XXX] to [XXX] in Grand Rapids, MN, in autonomous mode and was followed by 2 people riding on scooters. As the May shuttle made the turn, the VRUs were traveling in the same direction as the May shuttle on opposite sides of the lane. As the May shuttle completed the turn at 10 MPH, the brakes were applied and the vehicle came to a complete stop because one of the riders attempted to cross over in the lane which caused VRU safety buffer to intersect with vehicle path, which led the vehicle to slow to a stop. The scooter rider contacted the rear left rear bumper of the shuttle. Scooters were traveling at an estimated speed of 12 mph and accelerating.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was proceeding westbound with the right of way on a green traffic light at the six way intersection of [XXX], [XXX], and [XXX], when a person operating an electric scooter ran a red light and proceeded northbound into the intersection. The scooter made contact with the left rear quarter panel of the Zoox vehicle, at which time the Zoox vehicle had disengaged from autonomous mode. The Zoox vehicle pulled over, and police and emergency services arrived at the scene. Zoox is submitting this updated report to correct a previous reporting error in the HIGHEST INJURY SEVERITY field and to update for additional information received in August 2022.
